            "answer_text": "Well, why shouldn\u2019t they be? Armenia is neighbouring Iran and the last 2600 years Armenia was most of the time part of Iran (until about 200 years ago when Iran lost the Armenian territory to Russia by the Treaty of Turkmenchay, with several breaks between). Furthermore, Anatolia was also populated by Greeks in the past, and the territory of the Armenians was also greater, so they were also neighbours to Greeks. You can visit Iran right now, go to Persepolis, the old capital city, and see Armenians on over 2500 year old reliefs. Even the name \u201cArmenia\u201d stems from Persian, while Armenians call Armenia \u201cHayastan\u201d. There are also Armenians living in Iran. one of many Armenian churches in Iran, Armenian Vank Cathedral in Esfahan:  relief on the over 2500 year old Apadana Palace in Persepolis (near Shiraz, Iran), depicting an Armenian, bringing wine to the Persian Emperor Dariush the Great during the Noruz festival:  Behistun Inscription (over 2500 year old rock relief in Iran), on this inscription, the oldest attestation of the name Armenia can be found:  ",
